III. Wells Fargo and Orix's Motions for Summary
Judgment
A. Summary Judgment Legal Standard
*9  Under Rule 56(c) of the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure,
summary judgment is appropriate when the pleadings and
record evidence show that no genuine issue of material fact
exists and that the movant is entitled to judgment as a matter
of law. Little v. Liquid Air Corp.,  37 F.3d 1069, 1075 (5th
Cir.1994). “[T]he substantive law will identify which facts
are material.” Anderson v. Liberty Lobby, Inc., 477 U.S. 242,
248, 106 S.Ct. 2505, 91 L.Ed.2d 202 (1986) . Only disputes
about material facts will preclude the granting of summary
judgment. Id .
The burden is on the summary judgment movant to prove that
no genuine issue of material fact exists. Latimer v. SmithKline
& French Lab.,  919 F.2d 301, 303 (5th Cir.1990) . If the
non-movant bears the burden of proof at trial, the summary
judgment movant need not support its motion with evidence
negating the non-movant's case. Rather, the movant may

